== Game notes == === Troy === {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Troy |R1=7 |R2=7 |R3=0 |R4=0 |Home='''Bowling Green''' |H1=0 |H2=7 |H3=7 |H4=17 }} {{See also|2009 Troy Trojans football team}}
The Dave Clawson era at Bowling Green began with a home contest against the [[Sun Belt Conference|Sun Belt's]] [[Troy Trojans football|Troy Trojans]] in the first meeting between the two schools. The game was also the first time that Bowling Green opened the season at home since 2003. The Falcons came into the game as a 7-point underdog.
Troy received the opening kickoff and marched 80 yards down the field on ten plays in just under two minutes, led by Troy quarterback Levi Brown, who had played under Clawson at [[Richmond Spiders football|Richmond]]. Troy running back DuJuan Harris finished off the drive, running the ball in from two yards out to put Troy up 7&ndash;0. The teams would trade punts on the next two drives before Bowling Green pushed the ball into Troy's territory. After completing a pass on fourth and six to Troy's 25-yard line, [[Tyler Sheehan]] was intercepted by Troy defensive back Bryan Willis ending the Falcons' deepest drive of the first quarter. Troy would push their lead to 14&ndash;0 after Brown hit wide receiver Jerrel Jernigan for a 13-yard touchdown. The Falcons would answer on the following drive, as Sheehan hooked up with senior wide receiver Freddie Barnes for a 31-yard touchdown pass cutting Troy's lead to 14&ndash;7. Late in the second quarter Troy drove deep into Bowling Green's territory, but their drive stalled at the Falcons' 17-yard line after the Trojans failed to convert on fourth and one. The Falcons would run the clock out and end the half trailing 14&ndash;7<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff | first = | title = Humbling start | publisher = [http://www.troymessenger.com Troy Messenger] | date = September 3, 2009 | url = http://www.troymessenger.com/news/2009/sep/03/humbling-start/ | accessdate = September 5, 2009}}</ref>
The Falcons would show a totally different look in the second half effectively shutting the door on the Troy's offense, including forcing a fumble and intercepting Brown twice. The Falcons scored on their second drive of the third quarter, as Sheehan found Barnes for eight yards and their second touchdown of the game. On the first play of the fourth quarter, senior defensive back Roger Williams intercepted a Levi Brown pass at Bowling Green's 29-yard line. Bowling Green would take the lead on the following possession, as freshman kicker Jerry Phillips converted a 21-yard field goal making the score 17&ndash;14 in Bowling Green's favor. Bowling Green would score on its second consecutive possession, as junior runningback Willie Geter capped off a 4 play, 49 yard drive with a one yard rush, increasing the Falcons' lead to 24&ndash;14. Bowling Green freshman defensive back Adrien Spencer sealed the win for Bowling Green after he picked Brown off on a fourth and four and took the ball back for a 64-yard interception return for a touchdown, increasing the score to 31&ndash;14.<ref>{{cite web | last = Carle | first = Jack | title = Clawson, Falcons win opener | publisher = [http://www.sentinel-tribune.com Sentinel-Tribune] | date = September 4, 2009 | url = http://www.sent-trib.com/stnew/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4144:falcons-clawson-win-opener&catid=22:bgsu-sports&Itemid=40 | accessdate = September 5, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>
During the game, Bowling Green senior wide receiver Freddie Barnes set the school record for most receptions in a game, as he collected 15 receptions for 157 yards and Clawson became the eighth consecutive coach to win their debut as the head coach at Bowling Green.<ref>{{cite web | last = Emmons | first = Donald | title = Bowling Green upsets Troy | publisher = Toledo Blade | date = September 4, 2009 | url = http://www.toledoblade.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090904/SPORTS03/909049966 | accessdate = September 5, 2009}}</ref>
